<P ALIGN="CENTER"><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="GREEN"><I>Rig Veda</I>, tr. by Ralph T.H. Griffith, [1896], at sacred-texts.com</FONT></P><HR></p>  <h3 align="center" align="center">HYMN LXXXV. Indra-Varu&#7751;a.</h3>  
<p>1. FOR you I deck a harmless hymn, presenting the Soma juice to Varu&#7751;a and Indra-<br> A hymn that shines like heavenly Dawn with fatness. May they be near us on the march and guard us.<br> 2 Here where the arrows fall amid the banners both hosts invoke the Gods in emulation.<br> O Indra-Varu&#7751;a, smite back those-our foemen,yea, smite them withyour shaft to every quarter.<br> 3 Self-lucid in their seats, e&#146;en heavenly Waters endowed with Godhead Varu&#7751;a and Indra.<br> One of these holds the folk distinct and sundered, the Other smites and slays resistless foemen.<br> 4 Wise be the priest and skilled in Law Eternal, who with his sacred gifts and oration.<br> Brings you to aid us with your might, &#256;dityas: let him have viands to promote his welfare.<br> 5 May this my song reach Varu&#7751;a and Indra, and, strongly urging, win me sons and offspring.<br> To the Gods&#146; banquet may we go with riches. Preserve us evermore, ye Gods with blessings.</p>  
